//Airthmetic operators

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int num1 = 5;
        int num2 = 3;

        // Arithmetic operators
        int add = num1 + num2;
        int subtract = num1 - num2;
        int division = num1 / num2;
        int remainder = num1 % num2;
        int product = num1 * num2;
        int quotient = num1 / num2;

        System.out.println("Addition: " + add);
        System.out.println("Subtraction: " + subtract);
        System.out.println("Division: " + division);
        System.out.println("Remainder: " + remainder);
        System.out.println("Product: " + product);
        System.out.println("Quotient: " + quotient);
    }
}

different ways of incrementing a number
int num = num + 1;
int num = num + 2;
num += 1; --> same as num = num + 1
num *= 1;
num /= 1;
num %= 1;
num -= 1;


In both mathematics and programming, the modulo operation (a % b) returns (a) when (a < b), as (a) doesn't fully divide into (b), so the remainder is (a) itself.

postfix -> num++ -> assignment then increment
prefix -> ++num -> increment then assignment

examples

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int num1 = 5;
        int num2 = 6;
        
        int value_pre = ++num1;
        int value_post = num2++;
        //Arithmetic operators
        //num1++;
        
        System.out.println(value_pre);
        System.out.println(value_post);
        
        
    }
}

